Data Analysis About Academic Calandar

2Lazy2BeOriginal

2024-12-24

Summary

The University of Manitoba’s academic calendar traditionally is used as a guide for students and faculty. The course offerings are formatted with a department prefix (capitalized and generally 4 letters long) with a 4 digit code differentiating the various courses offered. Each course also has a title and a description that highlights the prerequisites, co-requisites and mutually exclusive courses.

This project explores the academic calendar as a dataset, focusing on the organization and relationships embedded within the course codes—four-digit identifiers that reflect the level, type, and sequence of university courses. Using a combination of keyword analysis, structural diagramming, and graph theory, we uncover the latent patterns and organizational logic behind the curriculum.

Our analysis includes:

  • A breakdown of how course codes are constructed and what information they encode.
  • A lexicon of common academic terms and categories, allowing for natural language analysis of course descriptions and requirements.
  • A graph-based model representing relationships between courses (such as prerequisites and co-requisites), programs, and departments.

Note: There are many courses that are no longer offered at the University of Manitoba and are still included in this document. The Academic Calendar does not differentiate between which classes are currently still offered or not.

Note: The University of Manitoba offers courses in French through the Université de Saint-Boniface. To distinguish these from their English counterparts, the course codes typically end in a 1. However, the academic calendar includes only a small subset of these courses—in fact, just three French-designated courses (ending in 1) are listed, suggesting that the majority are not featured in the central calendar.

Course Code analysis

This section explores the rationale behind the assignment of four-digit course codes at the University of Manitoba. Typically, course codes begin with a digit from 1 to 4, representing introductory (1000-level) to advanced undergraduate (4000-level) courses. However, there are exceptions to this structure, such as ENGL 930, which does not follow to the standard numbering convention. ENGL 930 appears to fulfill a specific administrative or curricular function, such as meeting a writing requirement. In this context, it may be helpful to interpret it as ENGL 0930, with an implied leading zero that aligns it with first-year or preparatory-level coursework. This suggests that the four-digit codes are rarely arbitrary chosen—often, the trailing digits are chosen for clarity, simplicity, or pattern recognition.

Perhaps surprisingly, the most common course code across departments is not 1000, but 4010, which appears in the course listings of 24 different departments. This may be unexpected—especially for those who might assume that introductory codes like 1010 or 1020 would be the most frequent.

This non-intuitive conclusion can be explained by sampling bias. While lower-level courses such as 1010 or 1020 may have more sections and larger enrollments, making them more known to students, the dataset reflects the number of unique departments using each code—not the number of students enrolled or sections offered. In other words, 4010 is more widely adopted across departments, even if courses like 1010 are more commonly experienced by students. A helpful analogy is traffic patterns: similar to how you’re more likely to find yourself in rush hour due to the higher volume of cars in a shorter time window, you’re more likely to encounter popular introductory courses—but that doesn’t mean they’re the most broadly used across all academic units.

An interesting observation is that the most common course codes often share identical frequencies, resulting in several ties. For example, within the Arts faculty—which comprises 38 departments—the top two most common codes, 2200 and 2600, are tied with 11 occurrences each. Another notable feature is the wide diversity of course codes in the ranking, with none appearing more than twice.

In contrast, within the Science faculty, the most common codes appear quite similar. However, this similarity is misleading, as these codes actually represent the same course offered by different departments. Specifically, these courses pertain to work terms for co-op placements, reflecting a unique administrative overlap rather than distinct academic offerings.

It’s worth noting that the School of Arts consists of only two departments, which limits the variation in course code frequencies. Because of the small size, ties in the most common codes are more likely as there is an upper bound. This illustrates how faculty size plays a crucial role in the distribution of course codes, and why ties can appear more frequently in smaller groups simply due to the limited number of possible outcomes.

For those curious, the course code 4010 ranks only around the middle of the pack when grouped by individual faculties—typically appearing as the 3rd or 5th most common code once. It emerges as the most common course code when all faculties are combined. This occurs because 4010 is consistently used across many different faculties, so while it may not dominate within any single faculty, its widespread presence across multiple departments accumulates to give it the highest overall frequency. In other words, its moderate but broad usage leads to it topping the combined rankings, illustrating how aggregation can highlight patterns that are less obvious within individual groups.

Which department shares the most classes with another

Each department’s course code corresponds to exactly one specific course (e.g., MATH 1500 refers to Introduction to Calculus, and LAW 1500 refers to Property). Given this relationship, a natural question arises: which departments have the most overlap in their course codes?

library(dplyr)


createOverlapCodeMatrix <- function(df) {
  # BIOE appears twice in both agriculture and bio engineering and since faculty doesn't matter, remove engineering for simplicty
  df <- df %>%
    filter(!(dept == "BIOE" & faculty == "engineering"))
  # Only departments with ten or more classes are considered 
  largeDeptVec <- names(which(table(df$dept) > 10))
  # symmetric matrix where each i,j entry is a pair of departments
  mostCommonMatrix <- matrix(nrow = length(largeDeptVec), ncol = length(largeDeptVec), dimnames = list(largeDeptVec, largeDeptVec))
  # iterate through each possible pair
  for (y in 1:length(largeDeptVec)) {
    for (x in 1:length(largeDeptVec)) {
      # name for department 1 and 2 
      target1 <- colnames(mostCommonMatrix)[[x]]
      target2 <- colnames(mostCommonMatrix)[[y]]
      # combine the two department codes
      combinedVec <- df %>%
        filter(dept == target1 | dept == target2) %>%
        pull(code) 
      temp <- table(combinedVec)
      # The table will only return either 1 (no overlap) or 2 (only occurs if both courses use same code)
      mostCommonMatrix[y,x] <- sum(temp == 2) 
      
    }
  }
  mostCommonMatrix
}
commonMatTest = createOverlapCodeMatrix(all_courses)
diag(commonMatTest) = rep(0, ncol(commonMatTest))
                          
which(commonMatTest == max(commonMatTest), arr.ind=TRUE)

Analyzing digits

As mentioned earlier, the course codes are not assigned arbitrarily—there are noticeable patterns in their usage. For example, even-numbered codes appear to be favored over odd-numbered ones. Let’s now visualize this trend using barplots and pie charts

## Conclusion for digits used

Trailing digit

It is somewhat surprising how heavily the digit 0 is favored as the final digit in course codes. However, this preference aligns with our natural tendency to favor round numbers. Codes ending in 0 are easier to categorize, remember, and organize mathematically, as we are accustomed within a base-10 system. This pattern is clearly reflected in the accompanying pie chart, which shows a disproportionately high use of codes ending in 0 compared to other digits.

Middle digit(s)

When examining the second and third digits, there is less consistency across departments, but a few informal patterns emerge. It appears common practice to increment course codes by 10 to indicate a continuation or second part of a course (e.g., 2210 following 2200), and by 100 to signal a shift to a different but related topic or level (e.g., 2200 to 2300). This structured numbering helps both administrators and students recognize relationships between courses at a glance, even if the system isn’t rigidly enforced university-wide.

An excellent example of structured course code usage can be found in the Computer Science department. COMP 1010 (Introduction to Computer Science 1) and COMP 1020 (Introduction to Computer Science 2) are directly related and designed as sequential prerequisites, with the increment of 10 clearly signaling a continuation. Meanwhile, COMP 1500 and COMP 1600 focus on different topics, and the differing second digits likely serve to distinguish between subject areas within the same level. Additionally, COMP 1012 (Computer Programming for Scientists and Engineers) covers similar introductory content but is tailored to engineering students and is not a direct prerequisite for COMP 1020.

That said, this pattern is not applied consistently—even within the same department. As courses progress into the second and third years, the use of the second and third digits becomes less predictable, suggesting that while course codes may reflect structure in some cases, exceptions are common and likely driven by administrative or historical factors.

It is worth noting that the mindset between determining course codes could change overtime which might be true in this case as the courses mentioned were offered overtime

Leading digit

The distribution of course levels reveals that third-year courses are the most commonly offered. As shown in the chart, this makes sense within the academic progression: first-year courses focus on fundemtal material with little room for specialization; second-year courses begin to branch out but still emphasize core topics. By the third year, students are academically prepared to choose from a wider range of specialized courses, increasing the volume of offerings at that level. In contrast, fourth-year courses are often more niche, with stricter prerequisites, which naturally limits their availability and enrollment.
